RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Emma BCBA  Ryan RBT    Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client stayed in his room during the entirety of the session. BCBA and RBT attempted to communicate with client through the closed door but client never responded.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Prompting    Notes:  BCBA and RBT started session by asking client about his favorite video games but client did not answer. Clients mother had mentioned that client enjoys a city building game on his Nintendo switch, so BCBA and RBT attempted to ask questions about the game, but client did not respond. RBT and BCBA asked client if he enjoyed any board games, and when client did not answer, BCBA and RBT started discussing the game Risk to try to get client to join the conversation. When client did not respond, BCBA and RBT asked if client played Mario kart. Client’s mother said that client enjoys Mario Kart. RBT and BCBA started asking client what character was his favorite but client did not answer. RBT and BCBA discussed a few characters within the game but client did not respond. RBT suggested that client should check out the game Age of Empires 2 if he enjoys world building games but client did not respond. BCBA told client that for every 5 minutes, BCBA would set an alarm and remind client that he could talk through the door. BCBA attempted this 4 times to no avail. BCBA and RBT asked client to just say one word and then they would leave client alone for 10 minutes. Client knocked on the door so RBT and BCBA decided that that counted and gave the client 10 minutes of no questions. BCBA and RBT attempted to ask client what his favorite movie was and stated that they would reward the client with 10 more minutes of no questions again, if he answered. Client did not respond. BCBA then wrote a note saying “hi is it ok if we write to each other instead?” BCBA and RBT heard client moving around with the paper in his room, but client never returned the paper or pen and never responded. RBT and BCBA ended up writing another note telling client that they were leaving and hoped that he would talk to them next time. RBT and BCBA waited for a response but did not get one.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Ryan RBT    Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client stayed in his room during the entirety of the session. RBT attempted to ask client questions to build rapport and client answered a few questions.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Prompting    Notes:  RBT arrived at clients house, to which client continued to stay in his room, with the door closed. To establish communication, RBT told client that RBT would ask one question and it would be a yes or no question. If client knocked on the door once, that would indicate a “yes” response, and two knocks would indicate a “no” response. If client answered the question then RBT would set a timer for 15 minutes to ask the following question. If client did not answer the question then RBT would set a timer and ask the same question 5 minutes later. RBT asked client if he had checked the video game Age of Empires 2 from their last session but client did not answer. RBT set the timer to 5 minutes and asked the question again when the timer went off. Client knocked on the door twice and RBT joked that client should have checked it out. RBT set the timer for 15 minutes. When the timer went off, RBT asked if client wanted to communicate using his voice or by writing notes to each other and passing it through the bottom of the door. Client knocked once indicating that he wanted to use his voice. RBT joked for the next 15 minutes that he couldn’t wait to ask client the question. RBT then asked client what his favorite video game was and client answered but RBT couldn’t hear him. RBT stated he couldn’t hear client but client didn’t answer again. RBT said that client technically answered the question so he could have 15 minutes again but RBT would ask the same question in 15 minutes. Client laughed. RBT asked the same question 15 minutes later and RBT couldn’t hear clients answer again. Client repeated the answer twice for RBT and said Borderlands. RBT set the timer again. RBT then asked what YouTube videos RBT should watch and client said to check out the story of Borderlands, but to start with the first one. RBT played videos of youtubers explaining the game and client laughed along. After 15 minutes and at the end of the session, RBT asked client if next session, RBT could watch client play Borderlands but client said “no I’m not ready for that.” RBT said goodbye and client said goodbye.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Ryan RBT     Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client progressing     Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Prompting,Verbal Behavior Training    Notes:  RBT arrived at clients home. Client was in his bedroom with the door shut. RBT then told client that he would be asking questions, in which, the client would answer by knocking on his door, one knock for yes, two knocks for no and RBT would ask each question every five minutes. These were the questions with each response:  1. Are you awake? Client answered yes.  2. Did you have a good day at school yesterday? Client answered no.   3. Are you tired? Client answered yes.   4. Are you afraid of the dark? Client answered no.  5. Have you ever had surgery? Client answered yes.  6. Are you excited for the new Spider-Man movie? Client answered no.  RBT then told client that he would be asking questions that the client would have to answer vocally. RBT told client that if he answered each question that RBT would give client a 10 minute break, but if client did not answer, then RBT would continue asking the question, until it was answered. RBT then asked client if he knew who Luke Skywalker‘s father was. Client did not answer, so RBT continued asking client the same question every 30 seconds. Client continued to not answer, even though RBT would say clients name and also knock on clients door. After 10 minutes, RBT change the question to ask if client knew what Iron Man‘s real name was. RBT continued to ask this question for another 15 minutes but client did not answer. RBT then asked client if he would rather knock on the door for his answers, than answering vocally, client knocked on the door “yes.” RBT then ask the following questions with these responses:  1. Do you text with your toes? Client answered no.  2. Did you have a gorilla attack you? Client answered no.  3. Are you awake? Client answered yes.  4. Are you awake? Client answered yes.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Ryan RBT     Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client progressing     Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Prompting,Verbal Behavior Training    Notes:  RBT arrived at clients house and client was in his room with the door closed. RBT asked yes or no questions, every 6 minutes. Before every question, RBT asked client if he was awake, and client answered yes every time. RBT gave client the option of either answering the questions vocally or by knocking on the door. These were the questions asked and the responses:  1. Are you tired? Knocked yes.  2. Did you have a good weekend? Knocked no.  3. Do you think the Patriots win tonight? Knocked no.  4. Did you watch your brother play soccer? Knocked no.   5. Have you ever been bitten by a radioactive spider? Did not respond the first time. However, on the second attempt he knocked no but laughed.  6. Do you think you could survive a zombie apocalypse? Knocked no.  7. Did you play any video games this weekend? No response. Then knocked yes.  8. Did you play Borderlands? No response. Then knocked yes.  RBT then decided to switch the questions to more open ended questions to try to have client answer vocally. If client answered the question, RBT would wait 4 minutes to ask another question. If client did not answer, RBT would as the same question for a total of 10 minutes, but would ask it every 2 minutes. Here were the questions asked with the responses:  1. Who is your favorite super hero? No response 5 times.  2. What is your favorite movie? No response 5 times.  3. What is your favorite movie? Did not respond 5 times.  RBT told client that he was about to leave and client spoke to RBT and told RBT that he did not have a favorite movie. Client also told RBT that his favorite superhero was Squirrel Girl. RBT complimented client on liking an obscure character in Marvel comics and client laughed. Client also told RBT that if they ever faced in Borderlands that RBT would need a lot of practice because RBT would need to use a different strategy to defeat client. RBT and client went back and forth talking about the differences between Call of Duty to Borderlands and exchanged some jokes and laughed.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Ryan RBT     Location:  Community    Current Clinical Status:  Client progressing     Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Visual Support,Self Management    Notes:  RBT arrived at clients home and started to observe client prepare a package to be mailed out. Client sold an item on eBay and was going to send it to the buyer. Mom helped client prepare the package, and client had difficulty following the steps of preparing the package.  Client was able to print out the shipping label, but had difficulty stuffing the box with crumpled paper so the toy wouldn’t move around in the box, so mom ended up doing it for him. Client also had trouble doing the taping so mom ended up doing it for him. Clients mom told RBT that they would be going to the post office to drop the package off, and then they would end up going to Savers, so client could buy a toy. While getting ready to go, mom asked client to first get his socks then put his shoes on for the trip. Client ended up only putting his socks on and came to the car with only socks. Mom told client to go back and get his shoes on, which client did. RBT went on the ride with client and his mom to the post office. RBT went with client inside of the post office and client dropped off the package properly, and also asked for a receipt. Afterwards, clients mom brought client and RBT to the Savers in West Roxbury. Mom told client that he had a time limit of 17 minutes to buy a toy, and gave client 6 dollars and a coupon. RBT went with client inside of the store and client went to the toy section and began searching for Baby Einstein toys. Client paced the aisle 4 times up and down and told RBT that sometimes he has to look behind certain items to make sure he’s not missing an opportunity to buy a toy. Eventually client discovered a drum set that was on the show, and decided to buy the item. While at the checkout, client provided his coupon and paid for the item with no issues. While on the car ride back to clients house, RBT and client discussed kinetics and Baby Einstein’s. Client explained to RBT about the rarity of certain items. When mom, client and RBT arrived at clients house, RBT and client went to clients room, where they further discussed all of clients toys. Also, client ended up discussing his favorite movies, and told RBT that he loved horror movies, client told RBT that his favorite was the movie It and Finals Destination.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Ryan RBT     Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client progressing.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Positive Reinforcement,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting    Notes:  RBT arrived at clients home and RBT, client and clients mom discussed what would happen in session. Client was to watch a tv show that was not preferred, and client would not be able to look at his phone during the episode. Client would have a break of 15 minutes after the episode to do as he pleased. In between both episodes, RBT and client would go for a walk down the street to pick up branches for the fireplace. After the walk, client would watch another episode, then he would have free time for the rest of session. Mom decided that having two comedy shows would be best to start, so the two shows that were selected were B Positive and Neighborhood. Before the first episode of B Positive, client procrastinated for 5 minutes. Client ended up giving RBT his phone and began watching the episode. During the episode, client ate a snack and was attentive throughout the episode. Client was not very responsive when asked questions during the show, but client did laugh at a few of the jokes. After the episode, client immediately grabbed his phone and began looking at eBay throughout the duration of his free time. Client also mentioned that he really wanted to become number 1 for having the best kinetic collection. Afterwards, RBT and client began their walk, where they both collected dry branches. During the walk, client made jokes about the shape of the street and also told RBT about the owl outside of his window during the night, to which client recorded it. After the walk, client began watching an episode of The Neighborhood with RBT. Client gave RBT his phone and was attentive towards the episode. When asked questions about the show, client didn’t seem interested. Client did laugh at a few jokes, but also admitted that he didn’t understand some of the humor. Client also said that he was worried about how in the future, someone might make a joke, and that client doesn’t want to come off as awkward if he doesn’t find it funny. Mom and RBT told client that he can fake laugh/smile and that it’s normal to be in that situation. After the episode client went directly to his phone and began looking on eBay. Client then began playing pinball and tried to beat the top score.

Discussed client wanting to start sessions a little bit later due to having to come home and have staff already be at his house when he arrives.  We discussed a few different options for sessions.   In addition, we also discussed client's limited interests in other items or activities other than highly preferred activity.  He currently is hyper focused on making sure he does not miss a bid to buy specific items.  He also spends a great deal of time outside of sessions talking with other people around the world that are interested in this specific item/activity (i.e., baby Einstein).  We discussed ways to incorporate expanding his interests and finding a balance between highly preferred item/activity and engaging in other activities.   In addition, discussions and strategies were discussed in regard to increasing activities of daily living skills.  He currently requires verbal prompting to complete activities and requires several verbal prompts to complete each step.  Discussed identifying whether it is a deficit in completing the skill or a need for motivation to complete.  Some of the issue, is that he is on his phone or appears to be thinking about preferred activity and checking if a new item was up to bid on.  Strategies that were discussed is having him complete the activity first and then giving him his phone after it's completed.  We also discussed the location of the visual/list for him to complete.  After a period of time, it appears that the visual is no longer stands out to him as a reminder.  Discussed putting visuals for brushing teeth in the bathroom as opposed to his bedroom door.   Also discussed social skills.  Client has difficulty retaining information after a short period of time.  Repetition of skills is required, and additional support is required.  Social interactions can be difficult as they are changing within each interaction and within each person you are interacting with.  It would be beneficial for client to have a list of questions in which he could remember to ask during social interactions.  This can be worked on during 1:1 sessions with RBT. RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Ryan RBT     Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client progressing.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Response Interruption/Redirection (RIRD),Visual Support,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting,Verbal Behavior Training,Self Management,Functional Communication Training (FCT)    Notes:  RBT arrived at client’s house and client stayed in his room with the door closed for the entire session. RBT began sitting in silence for about 20 minutes, and then passed a note to client, through the door, asking if client wanted to answer one question with the door cracked open, or one question with the door wide open. Once client answered the question, the session would be over. Client ended up texting his mom and told her that session was boring because questions were not being asked. Mom came upstairs and began asking client to open the door. Eventually client began talking to mom and RBT through the door, and expressed that he was afraid to open the door. RBT assured client that sessions would not be difficult, and would be more fun. Mom asked client if he was afraid of opening the door because it would feel like ABA would have won, and client said yes. RBT told client that that would not be the case, because RBT just wants to help client and also have fun with client. Mom had to go back downstairs, and client and RBT had a conversation for about 10 minutes. RBT told client that the goal is for the door to be opened, but also, client did an excellent job at conversing with RBT, and also advocating for himself. Also, during the session, client made a paper plane as a joke to the note RBT wrote to him, and RBT and mom were flying it around jokingly. Client laughed at several jokes made by mom and RBT.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Client  Staff    Location:  Clinic    Current Clinical Status:  Client is silent, and is shy.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Visual Support,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting    Notes:  Client did not speak, however he loves trucks. He came in was skeptical about everything, however, when he seen the trucks he was happy and began playing. Client likes to be tickled. Client does not like noise, he covers his ears to signify his disliking of it. As well as, when I put my hand in front of the truck he was playing   with, I asked what do you say and he said, “thank you”. I then said “No what do you say and said can you move please.” After, he then repeated it, but I tried again and   continued to just say, “thank you” and I repeated the steps I did prior ,to prompt him to say “Can you move please.” However, this time around, he ignored me. Also, client has tendency to run away or escape and I had to ensure to stay leveled to be able to get up and run as quickly as possible. When he needed help, with the small cars, he did say “I need help” independently. Took him about an hour to move from the corner to the middle of the room. Client is responsive when asking a question, he says yes or no. However, client does mimic, what is being said to him. After an hour, client became more comfortable and was a lot more verbal. Client picked up the Cookie Monster, and identified him, however when it came to putting it back, he through the doll. After times of saying no, after throwing the Cookie Monster and not putting it in the right location, I just put it where it belonged myself. Also, client seemed frazzled, so I asked “what do you need” and he whispered something under his breath, 3 times, I could not make out what was being said. He loves cause and effect toys, he used the dinosaur one and pressed the button, repeatedly. When I put my hand in front of him, he did not like it, he pushed my hand away. I asked, “what do you say”, he ignored it and continued pushing my hand. I did it again and asked, he tried pushing my hand, and still stayed there and I promoted him to say, “move please” and he complied. He likes to toss toys when done. When it was just him in the center by himself, he became more comfortable to move around the mat more to play. At one point, when snow was falling harder, he kept moving closer to the door, however I blocked his way, so he had no access to escape. Became really comfortable by himself, willing to explore more in the center, got him to go to the ball pit(which he liked a lot), sat on a bean bag, and played with the bouncy ball. Staff helped bring a bin to put balls in bin, since they were out the pit and he seemed to like that idea, so bin was left and helped to clean with the bin.  When it came to washing his hands, he did everything independently. Had chicken nuggets, sat at table and independently ate everything, needed no assistance. After finishing all nuggets, he had the choice between Cheetos, Oreos, and cookies, he chose Cheetos. He likes to open Oreos to separate them and eat each half by itself. When he wanted the Cheetos, he gestured for the Cheetos by saying “eat” and pointed. Every time he needed water, I would ask and he said “no”, however when I opened it, he independently drank it and closed the bottle after he was done drinking. Client likes to talk to himself. Client coughs while eating frequently. When in need of water, without me opening it for him, he opened, drank, and closed the bottle independently. Staff took him to the bathroom, client utilized it independently. At 5:19, tried to run out of door.

Session Participants:  Myself,Fernanda,Matteo,the father of client    Location:  Clinic    Current Clinical Status:  He was very energetic and was coloring animals on paper with colored pencils.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Discrete Trial Training (DTT),Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting    Notes:  This was my first session with Matteo and he did not seem skeptical at all of me on our first interaction. I asked him what activity he would like to start first and he said he wanted to color animals in a coloring book. I scan the page that he wants to color on the printer machine so the coloring book does not get ruined. After a few pages were colored, I told him we were not able to make anymore copies because we were running out of paper, he begun to breath heavily and demand coloring pages to be copied. He started to yell and scream and Fernanda came in and calmed him down using her amazing techniques of telling him to calm down or we can’t continue. He calmed down and we started to draw again. His father then came with his lunch and he started to pull out the food which was eggs and bread. Matteo did not like seeing the eggs and started to breath heavy and scream. His father quickly took the eggs away and Matteo started to eat the bread quietly, but slowly. After lunch, we lost the coloring book and he did not like that. He begun screaming and running around. I sat him down and told him to calm down and relax. He listened to me and I suggested we do a different activity to play. He chose to play a board game called brute light. When opening the box, he tossed everything out of the box making a mess. I told him to come help me clean it. He started to run back and fourth across the room and after a few minutes of asking him, he came and helped me pick the items up and put them into the box, his father then came and told him to put on his coat in which he did and the session was over.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Staff  Client  Mom  Dad  Sister    Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client is happy and engaging.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET), Prompting, Positive Reinforcement, Self Management, Modeling    Notes:  Client was watching helicopter video on iPad. Client enjoys watching trucks going by. When I put my hand in front of clients toy, I fully promoted him to say “move please.” Client keeps putting his hand in his mouth, I have to repeatedly ask him not to bite his finger. Client was playing with trucks and staff gestured for him to play with a puzzle. Client was not as interested, so continued to play with trucks. Client was interested in magnets, and continued to play with that. He was very responsive   when it came to the staff and playing with the toys provided. Also, he was very   familiarized with the phrase, “move please”, utilized it all when it came to wanting staff to move away. Client was able to read some sight words independently. Client was able to complete a fill in the blank puzzle, with staff. At 2pm, Client was gestured to go eat, at first he ate independently without mom, then began to get aggressive. He started to yell and continuously slam the spoon on the plate. Mom came downstairs to help calm him down, he bit mom hard on the arm and continued to yell. He also bit his hand. Since client did not want to eat, mom went to make a smoothie, however, the noise aggravated even more  him and triggered his aggression to increase. He grabbed the Cheetos bag and threw it on staff. He wanted to grab everything to just throw, so staff had to help him not continue that, he tried to bite part of truck off in his mouth, staff removed truck from his hand. Aggression behavior continued for about 15-20 minutes, dad and mom both had to calm him down. Mom gave him another Cheetos bag, he then continued to eat it independently, by then he was semi calm. His finger still irritated, parents had to take him upstairs to change his bandaid. At 2:45, mom tried to get client to try a smoothie, which he typically enjoys, however he declined. Then staff just allowed him to continue to eat Cheetos and watch his videos on his iPad, until he was calm enough to continue with the session. Client really enjoys Cheetos. Staff prompted for him to go wash his hands, he was compliant. Client did not wash hands independently. At 3:12, mom tried to get client to drink smoothie at the table, client complied and sat at the table. The client wanted a blue cookie, but in order to have the blue cookie, client needed to drink smoothie. Client complied and drank the smoothie, while naming different animals. Client was still calm and no tantrum occurred. Client finished the smoothie. At 3:18, client ate the muffin independently. At 3:28, client told staff bathroom, which he used independently, and that was his first bathroom break since 11. Client barely ate. Mom assisted him in the bathroom. Typically, when client is all done with an item, he needs to be fully promoted to say all done. Client independently sorted out items and put all of them in the right cup. And then pointed  out his favorite color, which is yellow. Client gets distracted easily. Client needs to have a truck in hand, when told to do something, truck is like his safe item. Client did a good job identifying majority of his sight words, barely needed assistance to prompt him to say anything. Client had 19 correct and 12 incorrect.

Then towards the end of session we played with bubbles, and to get the client to help clean the mess made, I said, “Let’s clean up and then few can finish playing with the bubbles.” At first client was hesitant, but then he complied.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  RBT, client, mom, brother    Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client got picked up from school by mom due to having no bus driver to drive him home. RBT was waiting for client inside. Client came inside and got right to his afternoon routine. Mom stated client got in trouble at school for being silly today.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Visual Support,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting,Functional Communication Training (FCT),Differential Reinforcement    Notes:  Client and RBT completed afternoon routine together. RBT used gestural prompting as much as possible. RBT and client worked on folding blanket, folding laundry, recalling events, personal information, identifying community signs and their functions, making a snack, and taking a shower. Before taking a shower client engaged in silly behavior(looking in mirror and jumping up and down). RBT opened mirror to prevent this behavior. Client stopped. Shower routine was all gestural prompts. Client did not engage in any silly behaviors after the shower(jumping up and down on bed naked) like he has been doing in previous sessions. Client engaged in 10 counts of vocal stereotypy. Clients routine after the shower was 100% gestural. Putting clothes in hamper, put on underwear, put lotion on body, put on shirt and pants, put on deodorant. Client was then gestured to put his towel back in the bathroom. Following that, client completed the last three steps independently! These steps included: picking up the towel off the floor, closing the glass shower door, and closing the shower curtain. Client also engaged in three instances of starting a conversation. Those instances included: “it’s cold outside”, “tomorrow is Friday”, and “Jackie what are you doing”

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Staff  Client  Mom  Dad  Sister    Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client is calm and happy and playing with his trucks.     Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Visual Support,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting,Self Management    Notes:  Client was very engaged when staff walked in with his toys. Staff prompted him to the table, at first he was not compliant, but then he became compliant. Client responds well to first then step instructions. Staff told the client first let’s do this, and then you can play with trucks. Client independently said “okay”. Client and staff have been doing 10 minute interval activities, as in complete this activity and then he resumes to playing with his trucks for 10 minutes. The trucks was the positive reinforcement, whenever he was able to complete the 10 minute activity, he was rewarded with truck. When his 10 minute break timed was over, he would bring one of his trucks over and whatever truck he chose to bring with during that interval was the one used as the reinforcement for him to compete whatever activity the staff had for him. However if during the activity, client is not responsive or compliant, time then stops and restarts. Client answered 5 out of 8 emotions correctly. The 3 he got wrong, Staff had to fully prompt him on the right words. During one of his breaks, one of his toys was broken and then he independently said”help.” Then staff prompted him to say “I need help.” After 10 minutes was up, client then went to play with toys, and then asked for wipes, and then staff then fully promoted him, “I need wipes.” Once 10 minutes was up, he came to the table and it was time to write  and staff did a preference assessment on which item he preferred to use. It was between the marker and pencil and client chose the marker. Then when client got the marker he chose to open it with his mouth, and bit it really hard and staff took the marker away. Staff took the top off to show how to open the marker and then reclosed the marker and then  prompted him to open it properly. Then client was instructed to write down his name, and he was able to write down the first name independently and need a partial prompt in order to spell his last name. However after writing down his name several times, client was able to write and pronounce his first and last name independently. Also, client started to bite his finger and staff prompted him to stop biting and he immediately complied. Additionally, client then took his bandaid off his previously infected finger and mom had to take him to dad to put another bandaid on to protect his finger. Then client was brought back by mom, however started to yell “fix” and staff instructed him to “use his words”, however by fix the client wanted to put tape on his truck. Client and staff engaged in math for about 5 minutes, client was independently getting one part of the equation but after 3 questions of staff having to gesture him to ensure he counted the other side, he then independently was able to add both sides of the equations. Client and staff engaged in building a puzzle, client was a little distracted at first, however he was able to make it all the way to the end and was engaging. Client and staff was able to complete a whole puzzle and client was praised by staff. Client was responding to praise positively by smiling a lot. During puzzle, client was intensely scratching his pelvic area. Staff did give client hand sanitizer, however he kept scratching. At 7:30, client went downstairs to eat dinner, where mom fed him. He ate for about 20 minutes. Client came back to session, but very distracted, it was hard to get him back to being focused. As a result, staff gave him 10 more minutes to get the last minute jitters out the way, so he can calm down. Then the time was 8pm and staff laid out the plan for the last 1 hour with him and client independently said “okay.” Staff and client ready a book, however client was not as engaged, yet he still read the book along with staff when asked to do so. Client and staff at 8:30 will brush teeth. Client brushed teeth independently, however he did need staff to gesture to brush tongue. All in all, staff worked a lot of baseline with client and he was fairly consistent with everything he was told to do. Only problem was that he did get distracted fairly easily, however he was compliant. Staff and client read  another book, client was very engaged with that book, staff being able to exclaim and be loud excited the client, which also kept him interested in the book. However when the client was getting to excited he tried to touch the staff’s face. Staff had to keep redirecting him to stop.

Staff had to say “Ye” and client finished with “Yellow.” When timer went off, client knew immediately to tend to the speakers voice. Since one of the targets the client needs to work on responding with yes or no, the memory games, once he finds a “match”, he able to say “yes or no.” Client was able to peer play for about 25 minutes with his sister, which over what is expected, only 10 minutes is required and he did 25 minutes. During dinner, client independently used his utensil without mom feeding him and ate completely independently. That item was something he really enjoyed, so he did not need mom to feed him like she usually does. Client did bolt multiple times to get his trucks when asked to come to the table, after breaks. There are sight words, the client needs to work on, like see, he, want, he and we. Client was able to get see and he down, independently but still requires to be full prompted, for the other words. When the BCBA was running a program with him, client was scrolling for the right answer, when he was asked the question. Client was able to independently put on shirt and pants. BCBA had to fully physically prompt client while brushing, however he was able to independently turn on water and spit. Client was able to ask independently for help using three word sentences, which is something he usually needed to be prompted for. Client could not complete a task for 5 minutes, without getting distracted. Because client was denied access to bringing more trucks to the table, it resulted in him using aggression to property destruct one of his toy trucks. Staff did take ABC Data. Client competed a puzzle but did need help from staff, in order to not get distracted.

Notes:  During today's session, parent, home BCBA, school team chair, special education teacher, regular education teacher, school BCBA met to discuss client's current progress in school setting.  Parents are concerned that he is not being integrated into the typical education classroom with peers and requested meeting to discuss further.  School team has expressed that although the notes coming home from school are that client is having a "great" day, client is still engaging in aggressions towards peers.  Aggressions towards peers are in the topography of scratching other's faces (peers and adults) and causing harm to others.  Client is quick and unpredictable as to when he will engage in these behaviors.  According to the school data, this month, client has engaged in aggression 2x the month of March.  He is currently integrated during lunch and recess, however during these times, peers are not within close proximity.  In addition, discussions regarding when client has zero rates of behaviors for extended period of time, integration will be developed around appropriate times.  It was discussed during the meeting, client's current skills and understanding of verbal language provides a larger gap between typical peers, than years past.  When programming integration these will be factored in.  The next activity the client will most likely be integrated into will be snack time.    The conversation regarding the client's impulsivity and compulsive to complete specific activities were discussed. This information is helpful in planning client's medical appointment in April.  In addition, conversations regarding transportation was discussed.  Client is currently being transported by his father instead of specialized transportation from the school district.  The school district is currently in negotiation contracts with private bus company to assist in transportation for in-district students to school.  Further information will be relayed to client's parents via transportation division within the school system.        Reported by:  School team, parents and BCBA. RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Client  Staff    Location:  Clinic    Session Location:  Clinic    Current Clinical Status:  Client walked in happy and went straight for the ball pit.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Positive Reinforcement,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting,Verbal Behavior Training,Self Management,Functional Communication Training (FCT)    Notes:  Client came in happy and eager. Another RBT said, “Hi” and he responded “Hi” as well, but not the way desired. Client engaged in property destruction when it came to his items building the buckets here at the center. At first, he was sorting but then just pushed them. Client and staff cleaned up after. Client and staff engaged in a puzzle, client was able to complete for about 16 minutes. Client then asked for a snack, utilizing the three word sentences. “I want snack.” Then Staff used 2 step directions, by saying , “first this then this”. Client was compliant and finished the puzzle. After the puzzle, we calmed up the puzzle and put it back. After we went to go wash hands and he began to eat. While eating, Client said “I want water.”   When the client needed help to open the water bottle, he said, “I need help independently”. Also, client when he was all done with the water, he said, “all done.” Client was scratching his pelvic area aggressively. Client and staff engaged in safety videos, in which he was able to identify what red, yellow and green meant. At first client did have difficulty with yellow, but was able to get it independently. Client was able to engage in parallel play for about 10 minutes. When mom came, he greeted her with “Hi mommy.”

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Ryan RBT   Tina BCBA   Client   Client’s mom    Location:  Home    Session Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client was in his room with the door closed.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Positive Reinforcement,Response Interruption/Redirection (RIRD),Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting,Self Management    Notes:  RBT arrived and client would not respond to him. Client’s mom came upstairs and told client he could either have his door open and talk to BCBA and RBT, or he could have the door closed and play Risk. Client told mom that he did not want to do either. Client’s mom opened the door and told him that he needed to choose 1 or she would keep the door open. Client continued to refuse so mom kept the door open. Client yelled at his mom that he was mad at everyone and would not talk to anyone for the rest of session, and laid down in his bed. RBT tried to talk with client and explain the reasons for why opening the door and interacting was important but client did not respond. Mom waited a few minutes then reissued the choices and client agreed to play a game with the door closed, although he was reluctant at first. Client eventually started making jokes and fully engaged in the game.

RBT and BCBA tried to provide choices to client to terminate screaming behaviors, however they continued for several more minutes. Caregiver tried to engage in conversation with client, however client continued screaming.  BCBA provide support to parent and RBT and had them try to remove their attention for a period of time to allow client to terminate screaming.  After a few minutes, client calmed down and was able to attend to his options.  BCBA provided two options for client to complete prior to engaging in preferred activity. BCBA explained to caregiver that it appears his behaviors are being maintained by attention, access to tangibles and escape.  Removing attention while engaging in screaming appears it would beneficial.  In addition, delaying access to tangible item until he completes demand appears would decrease behaviors as well.  BCBA explained that although he is escaping demand for a period of time, the demand is still required to be completed prior to gaining access to his preferred item.    After client was able to complete initial demand, he was able to transition assisting in developing a visual schedule and following the activities on his visual schedule.  RBT provide additional instruction and praise when client completed activities. RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Client  Staff  Mom  Sister      Location:  Home    Session Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  Client was watching a video and eating cookies.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Positive Reinforcement,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting,Verbal Behavior Training,Self Management,Functional Communication Training (FCT)    Notes:  When staff appeared and said hi, client immediately said, “one more minute.” Staff gave him one more minute, then he used a three word sentence by saying, “I want bathroom”, couldn’t really understand, but he ended up walking to the bathroom, so I am assuming that is what came after, “I want…”. Client needed assistance in the bathroom and staff used full physical prompts. Client and staff tried to do a memory game, but client was too distracted  and needed consistent physical prompts, in order to continue the game. Staff first tried the receptive way of trying to ask which visual was safe vs. unsafe, client continuously chose the unsafe visual as safe. Staff had to full physically prompt him, that was unsafe, instead of safe. When it came to the safety signs, client was able to independently identify what was safe versus unsafe. Client was also able to engage without being distracted as well. Client is also able to state when his birthday is independently. Then staff presented client with a book, bed, and car and first was asked to ”show me…”, then staff used an expressive form as well and Client was able to identify fully what each item was.   Client ignored several instances when staff called his name. Client and staff then worked on sight word ID. Client is able to continuously get the sight words, “we and see”, however, “he, and want”, he needs continuous full vocal prompts. Client and staff was able to read a book for the sight word Id and client got all five words on the cover independently. Mom brought client a smoothie and client enjoyed it all. When client was done, he independently said “all done.” Client engaged in parallel play for about 28 minutes with sister. Within the 28 minutes, client and sister did a puzzle(tried to throw a puzzle piece at her), played ice(no maladaptive behavior) & bounced a ball(too excited, ended up throwing the ice game box). Client and staff had to stay calm body on the floor for about 5 minutes to help client relax, in that 5 minutes we read a book, to help him calm down. Client and staff started on nighttime routine around 7:15pm. Client still needs to be fully promoted for responding with yes or no. Client and staff engaged in some coloring, where client was able to color some signs based on he seen them. Client did not get as distracted as he usually does, coloring allows him to be fully engaged. Also, client was biting himself a lot today. When client was brushing teeth, only able to open water faucet, spit, and get toothbrush independently. Also client, needed partial physical help when it came to putting on his shirt and underwear and pj pants.

Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Response Interruption/Redirection (RIRD),Visual Support,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Verbal Behavior Training,Self Management,Functional Communication Training (FCT)    Notes:  There were two instances of challenging behavior during today’s session. Client engaged in non-compliance when asked to practice piano. This lasted about four and a half minute. BT guided client through calming breathing techniques until the client was ready to practice piano. The second instance of non compliance occurred when the client was denied access to phone. Non compliance lasted for about one minute. BT talked client through frustrating situation and agreed to have client work for phone time. There were no instances of tantrums during today’s session. Client worked on identifying five situations where someone was happy and why they were happy. Client independently answered correctly on all five trials. Client also worked on independently identifying five coping strategies. Client worked on listing frustrating situations, four of which the client listed independently, and one in which the client required full verbal prompting. Client did a good job maintaining conversation by asking BT questions (what and how) throughout session. Client was also able to independently label 15 community safety signs. Client needs to continue to work on transitioning to a non preferred activity and putting the phone down. Reinforcers used today were beyblades and card games as well as phone time.

RESULTNOTE: Session Location:  Telehealth    ABA Principles Covered:  x    Progress Toward Current Goals:  x    Recommendations:  x    Notes:  During today's session, BCBA met virtually with client's school BCBA and special education teacher to discuss progress in the home setting and in the school setting.  Client's special education teacher appears to have a strong relationship with client and he is able to share things with her that he doesn't typically share with others.  During today's meeting a lot of discussion regarding client's rules that he develops on his own as far as what he can do and what he can't do which really appears to be hindering him.  Once he makes a rule, he does not allow himself to change the rule (i.e., he has a rule that he can't ask someone for help, so now he won't ask anyone for help for anything).  It's unclear where these rules came from and how they developed.  Additional conversations regarding concerns regarding client's mental health and if mental health services would be beneficial to client's overall treatment.  Client's special education teacher mentioned and showed papers in which he gets "stuck" in thoughts and is unable to free himself from the thoughts.  Often times he will write the same thing over and over on worksheets/paper.  His special education teacher has been able to have him utilize an app on his phone to write down his feelings and he has used this app to write his feelings down over the course of a weekend.  Now his teacher is trying to have him share these thoughts and feelings with someone that can help him further.    In addition, it was also discussed that client spends a great deal of time up in at night texting to other peers that live all around the world that appear to be having mental health issues.  He shares some of the information they tell him to his special education teacher.  Discussions regarding having conversation with his parents to inform them of some of the information and the concern is team has.  It was decided that a meeting with his parents, school team and home BCBA would be beneficial.  Scheduling would most likely occur after school vacation.      Reported by:  BCBA    New or Increased Intensity, Duration or Frequency of Maladaptive Behavior:  None at this time    Medical/Therapeutic Appointments or Medication Change:  None at this time    Has client expressed an intention to harm self or others?:  None at this time

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  BT Danielle, Babysitter Nicole, Clients Father, and the Client E.R.    Session Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  The client benefits from ABA Therapy.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Visual Support,Prompting,Self Management,Functional Communication Training (FCT),Differential Reinforcement    Notes:  E.R. was in a positive mood when I arrived and seemed relaxed. He played with a sensory toy. Then he created a schedule with staff. He was reluctant to go outside because he went on a long hike today but when I introduced a bubble gun as a positive reinforcer he was more willing to go outside. The first task on his schedule was a work book of various puzzles and activities. E.R. was non compliant and ABC data was collected. He didn’t want to do the work book and stated that verbally to staff. Then he opened some sensory toys and played with them for a moment. I reminded E.R. of his positive reinforcers and he was willing to get back on task and move forward. E.R. then showed inflexibility with a schedule change. The staff and guardian were trying to find (and eventually found) batteries and a screw driver for the Bubble Gun. As this happened E.R. had a rigid attitude and was growling under his breath at staff. After the batteries were installed, his attitude shifted and he had a better day. E.R. talked with staff for one minute about flying vs super strength using a conversation prompt card. During this conversation he said “he wishes he had super strength so his dad doesn’t think he’s weak.”Then he took a break with the bubble gun. After that he went outside with staff, his younger brother, and his guardian for about 10 minutes. E.R. flossed his teeth with staff. E.R. was very energetic and often found himself off task. After flossing he took a break. During his break he played with his younger brother. They bickered slightly and E.R. said to his brother “don’t do that or I’ll kill you.” Staff and his dad prompted him advising that was inappropriate.  After break E.R. told staff 3 things about his day. He told staff about how he made a cake for the first time for his dad with his babysitter. He also told staff about his hike and about going outside on break and how he feels it went “really good.” While talking about these items, E.R. randomly asked his dad if he cries and why does him and his brother ever see their dad cry? Staff got E.R. back on task and we finished out conversation. Towards the end of the session E.R. had free time to play with sensory toys but instead he wanted to watch 15 minutes of TV before his mom comes for dinner.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  BT Danielle and client ER as well as his babysitter, younger brother, and dad.    Session Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  This client benefits from ABA Therapy.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Visual Support,Prompting,Self Management,Differential Reinforcement    Notes:  ER was watching tv with his younger brother and babysitter when I arrived. He immediately asked for more time but I was early so we compromised for 15 minutes. Then the first task was for ER to make his schedule. When it was time to stop watching TV, he was reluctant to cooperate. But after several reminders, he chose to participate. ER assisted in making his schedule and deciding what order he wants to do things. Today the wind is blowing pretty badly so ER completed some bug worksheets and talked about bugs with staff. We had a very good conversation about friendly bugs and why bugs are important for nature and our eco system. He did mention rare and dangerous bugs but each time one was mentioned, I would discuss a friendly and safe bug of the same type. (Spiders, bees, etc.) ER then worked on a scratch art astronaut and a space maze in his workbook. He tried to stay on task but was distracted by the TV being on in the room next to him multiple times. He did stay busy for that period of time however. ER chose to watch Total Drama Allstars on TV for his break. Then ER and staff played a round of social Jenga which went well with no issues. When it was time for one minute of socialization with staff, ER asked if he could do it without a prompt card. So ER talked to me for a minute straight about water squirt guns vs guns that spray bubbles. Then ER took his second break. ER’s younger brother was upset and disruptive but ER handled himself very well. When it was time to talk about 3 specific things about his day ER was non compliant. ER wondered around the house, bothered his brother, and hid in a cabinet. I tried to suggest positive reinforcers like the bubble gun or TV however he continued to be non compliant. ER then went into his dads room and hid in a laundry basket. Then he laid in his bed under a blanket. After that he moved back into his dads room and played with his dads laundry and clothes hamper. At about 4:30pm his dad got home from work and tried to talk to ER. ER hid in his dads closet. His dad tried to encourage ER to get back on schedule with offering cake after his session as a positive reinforcement. ER told me he rode his bike and then laid on the floor and wouldn’t tell me anything else. ER said multiple times that he is not happy. ER kicked and threw his toy. Then ER told me he rode his bike but he didn’t want to because the babysitter made him. ER told me he had breakfast when he woke up but didn’t want to talk about it. After multiple attempts, he told me he ate Cheerios. He told me he watched TV for his 3rd item and told me about a show called Battle Kitty after multiple attempts. After this, he agreed to floss. He walked over and grabbed the flossed but he did stomp his feet. He flossed two or three upper teeth and then moved on to his lower teeth. He usually flosses for around 3 minutes but he was done in less than one minute today. After he flossed his teeth he said he isn’t doing anything else. He threw his flosser away and watched tv. His dad advised me after the session that he may be tired because they have been with the babysitter since 7 am and spent a large amount of time at Planet Fitness.

Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Visual Support,Prompting,Self Management,Differential Reinforcement    Notes:  ER was watching tv when we arrived. Then he made his schedule for the day with the BCBA. He picked the order that he wanted to do his activities. ER told staff 3 things about his day and also said he had a “good day.” ER and the BCBA played a game called Spot-it. BCBA gave an example of good sportsmanship. ER did not win and he said “I hate this game” at the end of the round. Then he took a break and watched TV. When it was time to move to the next task ER became non compliant. The BCBA picked a word search for ER. Then ER did the word search and a maze. ER chose to go outside for his break so we stayed outside for his break and his goal. ER played with bubbles with his brother. Then ER flossed his teeth. ER had a 1 minute conversation with staff using a conversation prompt card. Then took break. He chose to skip the last 6 minutes of his break. ER then did a Dinosaur Exercise video. He seemed to be in an overall good mood and was smiling. He finished the day with watching an educational video on dinosaurs with his younger brother, and he talked to staff about “what was his favorite part of session today?” He said his favorite part was doing bubbles with the BCBA and me. At the end of the session, ER received a dinosaur toy as a positive reinforcer.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  BT Danielle, Client ER, Clients Grandmother, Clients Younger Brother, and Clients Babysitter     Session Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  This client benefits from ABA Therapy.     Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Modeling,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Visual Support,Prompting,Self Management,Differential Reinforcement    Notes:  ER arrived home from school in a good mood and said he had a good day. He got settled and did preferred activities before we got started. ER then made his schedule and picked the order of his activities. ER went outside with staff and played with bubbles. Then he played in the dirt with his brother. They were very nice to each other and had a great time. When it was time to come inside ER had to receive several reminders to come inside. But then he came inside and played a game. Today he played a one person drawing game but he had good sportsmanship while playing with his brother outside so I gathered data based on that. Then ER decided to play a game of Go Fish with staff. ER got upset that he was not winning when the timer went off. He said “I hate this” and “I hate everything.” He kicked a box and became non compliant. I gave ER an example of good sportsmanship. I let him know I’d clean up the game and let him cool off. ER took his break. ABC data was collected. After a 10 minute cooldown/break, he got back on schedule. ER then did a word search, a maze, and some bug worksheets. Then ER flossed his teeth with no concerns. ER then took another break. After his break, we talked about 3 specific things about his day. ER struggled with this task and had negative self talk. But was able to complete the task with assistance from staff. ER did tell staff he didn’t go to art class today because he was too embarrassed. ER compromised with staff to do a one minute convo so he could earn his positive reinforcer. (We were previously ending on 3 specific things about his day.) ER talked to staff about his favorite movie. When we completed that task, time was up and the session was over. ER seemed to be tired and his face appeared sleepy. ER received a dinosaur art kit as a positive reinforcer.

Session Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  This client benefits from ABA Therapy.    Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Prompting,Self Management,Differential Reinforcement    Notes:  ER was watching TV when I arrived. I made his schedule for him and he rearranged the order of activities. First he played two rounds of Crazy 8’s with staff. He won one round and lost one round but he had great sportsmanship the entire time. Then ER cleaned the bathroom sink. He was reluctant to do so and asked me “why?” multiple times. He didn’t know what to use for cleaner but with my  assistance he found Clorox wipes. He was able to perform the other steps independently however. He did ask me if I could hold the items from the sink while he cleaned under them, but I encouraged him to do it independently. Then he reluctantly had a one minute convo with staff. We used a prompt card but it was a card he picks often which is “what is your favorite movie?” Then he took a break and played with bubbles as a positive reinforcer. After that he told me 3 Specific Things About His Day. He told me he went to Art for part of the class today. After that he flossed. Today is the first time he did not need his flossing steps visual aid. He completed all of the flossing steps independently. Today it is rainy and cold so we could not go outside. Next ER did 3 Mazes and timed himself. After that he took a break. After his break he read a book for 10 minutes and stayed focused the entire time. At the end of the session, we talked about how our day/session went together. We both agreed that today was a great day and he was very focused and successful. At that time, our session came to an end.

RESULTNOTE: Session Participants:  Client ER, BT Danielle, clients babysitter, clients father, and clients younger brother.     Session Location:  Home    Current Clinical Status:  This client benefits from ABA Therapy. The client is engaged and receptive to positive reinforcers. He easily transitioned between the tasks on his schedule.     Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions,Positive Reinforcement,Task Analyses,Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET),Prompting,Self Management,Functional Communication Training (FCT),Differential Reinforcement    Notes:  When I arrived ER was walking home from school with his babysitter and younger brother. He settled in with a 5 minute TV break and we got started. ER made his schedule and picked the order. ER doesn’t like writing the words of the tasks so he instead drew a picture of each task. First he swept his dads room. He was able to get the broom out without any assistance. He didn’t sweep the whole room properly but he tried. Staff had to remind him to pick up clothes and sweep underneath them. Then he dumped the dust pan without assistance. While sweeping his dad arrived. Then ER cleaned the kitchen sink. He didn’t have any available cleaning products so we used a wet paper towel. Next we went outside. It’s very nice outside and he played with bubbles. When we first got outside, ER froze up and was reluctant to continue. But with some encouragement, he was fine and had fun with the bubbles. After being outside for 10 minutes, ER took a 8 minute TV break with his dad and younger brother. Then ER did a maze and timed himself. He only wanted to do one maze. He kept getting distracted by the TV being on in the living room. Then ER flossed his teeth. He did not need the visual aid today and successfully completed all the steps. After that ER played Go Fish with staff. He did lose and we did talk about good sportsmanship because he said “ohhhhh” in an upset tone when he lost. He also growled a few times during the round when I would successfully guess a card. But he did not act out other than that. Then he shook my hand, made eye contact, and said good game. Then he took a break and watched 8 minutes of TV. After that he became non compliant when it was time to continue his schedule because he wants to watch TV. I had to encourage him multiple times to tell me 3 Specific Things about his day. After some non compliance and reminders to stay on schedule, ER got back on task. After 3 Specific Things, we had a one minute conversation about “Our Favorite Superhero.” Then we wrapped up session talking about how our meeting/session went. Overall we agreed he had a good day but he could have had a better day. He did turn it around however and completed his schedule therefore earning a positive reinforcer which was a Harry Potter mystery keychain.

He was smiling but seemed a little tired. After his mom left he was upset for about ten minutes. He played with preferred toys such as the parachute. Then FJ ate breakfast. He ate all of the egg from two egg sandwiches and a couple of yogurt puff bites. FJ tried to do color matching boards and echoics in his blue high chair, and he got frustrated. He did remove several colors from the Velcro board independently but he didn’t match them or reapply them to the board. FJ did the task of putting bears in colored cups and he successfully independently put the bear into the cup two times. He listened to Wheels On The Bus two times and practiced signing “more” and “all done.” We practiced echoics and saying “mmm” and “mama.” At one point it did sound like FJ said “Mikey.” FJ sat at the table and looked at books for about 15-20 minutes and seemed to be focused the entire time. At about 9:40 am, FJ began yawning. At 9:45 am FJ had 5 ML of Children’s Tylenol with no issues. FJ listened to Wheels on the Bus and  5 Little Ducks. FJ approached a peer to color but didn’t seem interested in coloring when provided material. FJ has been yawning and rubbing his eyes. FJ had snack around 10:15 am. He independently approached a ball and kicked it multiple times. Then he entered the ball pit with a peer. He played in the ball pit. Then FJ watched 5 Little Ducks and practiced clapping his hands and signing for “more.” Then FJ played with bubbles with a peer. FJ tried to do work in the blue high chair again but got frustrated. FJ pushed a ball with staff and after a full prompt, he was able to push the ball. FJ then washed his hands with staff. Staff had to assist with all the steps. FJ then ate lunch. He ate about 75% of lunch. Then he played with educational toys and watched Wheels on the Bus. FJ watched 5 Little Ducks and practiced signing for “more.” Then FJ listened to music and looked at Mikey Mouse books. Around 12pm FJ became even more tired. He started sucking his thumb constantly and he laid his head on the table while he listened to music and looked at a book. Then FJ fell asleep at the table. I moved him from the table to his nap pad. He napped with his thumb in his mouth while he listened to educational music. Then his mom picked him up and session came to an end.

Behavior Analytic Interventions Used:  Antecedent-based interventions, Positive Reinforcement, Task Analyses, Visual Support, Naturalistic Environment Teaching (NET), Prompting, Self Management, Functional Communication Training (FCT), Differential Reinforcement, Modeling    Notes:  The BT met with ER in his residence.
